result.execSummary:
The defendant Carole N Wondra was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case.

  • Disorderly Conduct, a class B misdemeanor, Wisconsin Statutes 947.01(1).

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

supervisions.notes: The Court sentences the Defendant to pay a fine of $50  + costs = $516 (incl. DNA surcharge) to be paid in $50 per month installments commencing on 5/20/15 and on the 20th day of each month thereafter until paid in full. Non-payment shall result in a 10 day jail term, with Huber privileges consecutive, can be served in another county so long as at no expense to Jefferson County.

Case called at 1:29pm [mo]
Defendant Carole N Wondra in court with Attorney Karl Huebner.   ADA Theresa Beck appears for the State of Wisconsin.  
Maximum penalties recited; Constitutional rights given; plea of "No Contest" entered on Count #1 without the Domestic Abuse enhancer; factual basis stipulated; victim rights compliance verified, ADA Beck notes a Victim Impact Statement was not received from the victim; the Court accepts plea, finds Defendant guilty, and orders Judgment of Conviction entered.

The Court discloses, under SCR 60.04 that in the Court's former capacity as Jefferson County Assistant District Attorney, ADA Wambach/ his colleagues did prosecute Ms. Wondra. The Court does not feel that any disqualification or recusal is needed.

DNA surcharge) to be paid in $50 per month installments commencing on 5/20/15 and on the 20th day of each month thereafter until paid in full. Non-payment shall result in a 10 day jail term, with Huber privileges consecutive, can be served in another county so long as at no expense to Jefferson County.
